'''Lu Xun''' ({{zh-tsp|t=魯迅|s=鲁迅|p=Lǔ Xùn}}) or '''Lu Hsün''' ([[Wade-Giles]]), was the [[pen name]] of '''Zhou Shuren''' ({{zh-tspw|t=周樹人|s=周树人|p=Zhōu Shùrén|w=Chou Shu-jen}}) (September 25, 1881 &ndash; October 19, 1936) is one of the major Chinese [[writers]] of the 20th century.  Considered by many to be the founder of modern Chinese literature, he wrote in ''[[baihua]]'' (白話) (the vernacular) as well as [[classical Chinese]]. Lu Xun was a [[short story]] writer, [[Managing editor|editor]], [[translator]], [[critic]], [[essay]]ist and poet.  In the 1930s he became the titular head of the Chinese League of Left-Wing Writers in [[Shanghai]]. 
 
